Consider a right triangle $ABC$ with a point $F$ on its hypotenuse $AC$. From point $F$, lines are drawn parallel to the legs of the triangle, dividing it into a square $DFEI$ and two smaller right triangles $ADF$ and $FEC$. The area of triangle $ADF$ is given to be $m$ times the area of square $DFEI$. The problem asks to find the ratio of the area of triangle $FEC$ to the area of square $DFEI$, expressed as a common fraction in terms of $m$.$$ egin{align*} egin{tikzpicture}\draw (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (0,2) -- cycle;\draw (0,1.333) -- (2.667,1.333) -- (2.667,0);
ode at (0,2) [above left] {A};
ode at (0,1.333) [left] {D};
ode at (0,0) [below left] {B};
ode at (2.667,0) [below] {E};
ode at (2.667,1.333) [above right] {F};
ode at (4,0) [below right] {C};
ode at (1.333,0.667) {1};
ode at (3.333,0) [below] {s};
ode at (0,1.667) [left] {r};\end{tikzpicture}\end{align*}$$

Given a regular pentagon $ABCDE$, we want to determine the number of non-congruent figures that can be constructed by attaching two equilateral triangles to the pentagon in two of the five positions shown in the diagram below: egin{center} egin{tikzpicture}\draw (0,0) -- (2,0) -- (2.95,1.54) -- (1.9,3.24) -- (0.31,3.24) -- cycle;\draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (2,0) -- (1,-1.73) -- cycle;\draw[dashed] (2,0) -- (2.95,1.54) -- (4.59,0.81) -- cycle;\draw[dashed] (2.95,1.54) -- (1.9,3.24) -- (3.69,3.78) -- cycle;\draw[dashed] (1.9,3.24) -- (0.31,3.24) -- (-0.74,1.7) -- cycle;\draw[dashed] (0.31,3.24) -- (0,0) -- (-1.64,0.73) -- cycle;
ode[below left] at (0,0) {$B$};
ode[below right] at (2,0) {$A$};
ode[right] at (2.95,1.54) {$E$};
ode[above] at (1.9,3.24) {$D$};
ode[left] at (0.31,3.24) {$C$};\end{tikzpicture}\end{center}
